{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_electrum_ver02/data/sn95060997/00517018934/1911012701/0349.xml":{"full_text":"Arizona Range News\nVOL. XVII\nArizona Leads In Copper Production\nOUTPUT IS 300,000,000 POUNDS\nValued At $50,000,000.00 Annually\nIndustry Pays Net Profits of Between $15,000,000 and $20,000,000\nAnnually That Are Going Into the Bank Accounts of Share\nholders of Copper Companies In This Part of the\nSouthwest\u2014New Producers Coming In.\nOne of the most essential things in\nour present-day civilization is copper\nthe almost universal vehicle of trans\nmission.\nWell, the whole Territory is rejoicing\nin the fact that preliminary estimates\nof the United States Geological Survey\nhave again placed Arizona in the lead\nas the largest producer of copper in the\ncountry.\nMichigan long held first rank, then\nMontana came to the front and her\nmines were the foundation of the\ncolossal Amalgamated Copper Company.\nBut now Arizona outranks both States\nand annually produces upwards of 300,\n000,000 pounds, valued at about\n$50,000,000.\nThe year 1910 has given most re\nmarkable and unmistakable evidence of\nthe steady growth of the world\u2019s needs\nfor copper.\nConsumption for the year exceeded\nproduction, and this in spite of the fact\nthat the production was the greatest in\nthe history of the industry.\nMany of our readers are perhaps, not\naware of the gigantic proportions to\nwhich the copper industry has grown\nduring the last few years.\nWhen we realize that the production\nof copper has increased faster than that\nof any other industry in the United\nStates during the last ten years, and\nthat the domestic consumption of the\nmetal has increased about 50,000,000\npounds per annum during the last six\nyears, it gives us some idea of the\nmagnitude of the industry.\nEstimates based on figures for the\n4y!M\u00dfFj\u00dfMW*nyf^^\n\u2019^\"W -\u2018z '\u00abwM*\nswjpi^ ?^lij%|||^l^^\nIL6*^JS?eSW^\nt ^^e\u00dfmb^^m\u00dfbb^K^^^ 51 *1\n^wsSS\u00df\u00dfifeiK\n\"1* J^KH' '^RSf'\n>^W&^W^ay I ''jHfv\u25a0\nffirgp^\n^wM^K' f\nMB-\nW> W i ill I<l ^P-LZ? J MMI v\nf^^W\u00dfaw^r^^nWMWK jeSkEK^H\nX <^^BJHRH|MHjaj\u00bb^^''ji^^ jF*> tWW W\nbv j\u00bbs<wWWsi^^\nCooling Tower Above the Mascot Copper Company\u2019s Model Power Plant.\nWILLCOX, COCHISE COUNTY, ARIZONA, FRIDAY, JANUARY 27, 1911\nfirst eleven months of 1910, published\nby the Bureau of statistics and also by\nCopper Producers\u2019 Association, indicate\nthat the exports of copper will exceed\nthe exports for 1909, which amounted\nto 682,846,726 pounds, and that they\nmay be as much as 700,000,000 pounds.\nTen years ago it was less than half that\namount.\n1910 Consumption Exceeds Production\nDuring 1907, 1908 and 1909 the world\u2019s\nconsumption of copper lagged behind\nthe production on account of the de\npressed business conditions, which pre\nvented the financing of many enter\nprises that would have otherwise been\nlarge consumers of copper. As a result\nof the financial stringency during the\nyears mentioned, the visible supply of\ncopper a year ago had climbed to over\n300,000,000 pounds, but the return of\nprosperity created an enormous demand\nfor the metal, and as a result the in\ncreased production of 1910 was con\nsumed and the visible supply of copper\non hand at the commencement of the\nyear reduced about 100,000,000 pounds.\nIn other words the visible supply of\ncopper at this time is equivalent to a\nlittle more than two months\u2019 actual\nsupply!\nAll this speaks eloquently enough of\nthe world\u2019s great demand for the metal\nand makes it quite obvious that if\ncivilization is to continue its onward\nmarch it will not be long before copper\nconsumption will exceed production to\nsuch an extent as to cause a lasting\ncopper famine. As an evidence of this\nwe may cite the production from the\nso called porphyry mines, amounting to\nabout 170,000,000 pounds per annum.\nThe new production was not only\nlarge, but abrupt and ill-timed, as it\nmade its appearance in the metal mar\nket at a time when both this and\nEuropean countries were going through\na most radical business contraction,\nstarting, as it did, with the panic of\n1907. And yet, in the face of all this,\nthe year 1910 has not only consumed all\nthat was produced during the year, but\nhas absorbed about 100,000,000 pounds\nof the accumulated copper from pre\nceding years. This shows how fast\nconsumption overtakes increased pro\nduction.\nIndustry on Stable Basis\nIn covering this phase of the copper\nsituation in an article written recently\nfor the Boston Journal, N. L. Amster,\npresident of the Arizona Commercial,\nBoston and Corbin and Shannon Copper\nCompanies, remarked as follows:\n\u201cWe know that we are not likely to\nget any more such abrupt increased\nproductions as that of the porphyry\nmines, unless perhaps from the produc\ntion of new mines in Arizona, which\nare to come into the market about the\nmiddle of 1911. As against that we\nalso know there are older producers\nwhich are by degrees, giving out while\nthe new ones are coming in. Then,\ntoo, if we should get any sort of busi\nness improvement\u2014and it is my opinion\nthat we shall witness an improvement I\nearly in 1911\u2014we alone in this country\nwill use from 15,000,000 to 20,000,000 I\npounds more copper per month than we\ndid during 1910.\n\u201cIn other words, with improved busi\nness conditions, the United States will\nconsume from 180,000,000 to 240,000,000\npounds more copper in 1911 than it did\nin 1910 which will more than offset any\npossible increased production that we\nare likely to get in 1911 from the new\nArizona camps. Then there is the\nnatural increased demand from other\nparts of the world that must be con\nsidered, an increase which has been\ndemonstrated to be much more regular\nand more marked than even that of the\nUnited States. We can thus see that\nthe underlying condition of the copper\nindustry is very sound, and the future\nof the metal very bright.\u201d\nWhile the price of the red metal\nduring the year 1910 has been such as\nto give satisfactory returns to share\nholders in copper properties, should the\nsupply get down to a point where it\nwould equal only one month\u2019s consump\ntion, the price of the metal could not\npossibly be kept from advancing four\nor five cents per pound within a very\nshort time.\nArizona Will Maintain the Lead\nIt is believed that Arizona will not\nagain be headed by Montana, or by any\nother state in the Union.\nThe copper mines have brought fame\nto Arizona, and justly so, as there are'\nseveral good reasons why the copper\nindustry of this Territory is exceeding\nly attractive. Generally speaking, our\nores contain a high percentage of cop\nper and associated with the copper is\nconsiderable gold and silver. When we\nstate that there is often a sufficient\namount of the precious metals asso\nciated with the copper to pay for the\nmining, smelting and handling of the\nproduct, leaving the copper practically\nclear gain, we believe that further com\nment is unnecessary to make clear our\ncontention as to the attractiveness.\nAn Underground View Showing Where a Twelve-Foot Vein of High\nGrade Copper Sulphide Ore Was Recently Cut in the West Cross\ncut From the Consolidated Tunnel at the Mascot Copper Camp.\nSee Second Page for Particulars.\nfrom an investment standpoint, of the\ngreat red metal industry in this Terri\ntory.\nArizona\u2019s Production Worth $50,000,000\nWith an annual production of copper\nworth about $50,000,000 in Arizona from\nour mines, and the industry practically\nin its infancy in this Territory, we do\nnot hesitate to venture the assertion\nthat the time is not far distant when\ninvestors and the world will \u201csit up and\ntake notice\u201d of our great mineral re\nsources to a far greater extent than\never before.\nThink of it! Here is an industry\nwhich employs 25,000 men and supports\n100,000 human souls! It pays net profits\nof between $15,000,000 and $20,000,000\nannually that are going into the bank\naccounts of shareholders of copper\ncompanies in this part of the great\nsouthwest! A great percentage of this\nimmense wealth is produced in Cochise\ncounty. Startling? Yes; and nothing\nshort of a rigid investigation will con\nvince some persons that our statements\nare in every respect absolutely true.\nMascot a Coming Producer\nFor several years we have called at\ntention to these matters, and particu\nlarly as they apply to the Mascot Cop\nper Company. We have been in close\nproximity to this property and have\nhad every opportunity to watch and\nstudy each move that has been made to\nbring it from a flattering prospect to\nthe eve of production.\nWe have spent many years in Cochise\nCounty and Southeastern Arizona, dur\ning which time we have closely observed\nthe development of other copper pro\nperties, and according to our judgment\nthe property owned by the Mascot\nCopper Company has been developed\nalong as conservative, careful and pru\ndent business lines as any other pro\nperty in the Territory.\nIts improvements, both underground\nand surface, are of the most substan\ntial and permanent character, and the\nreason for all this will be apparent to\nour readers when they know what we\ndo regarding the management of the\nMascot.\nThere can no longer be any question\nas to the richness of the property or\nthe ore bodies contained therein, and\nwe do not believe there can be any\ndoubt as to the values contained in the\nore bodies not yet opened up.\nProperty Has Capable Management\nFor five years the management at the\nproperty has been under the adminis\ntration of Captain B. W. Tibby and E.\nA. Ely, consulting engineer and general\nsuperintendent respectively, and their\nability, from a business and practical\nstandpoint, has been favorably com\nmented upon by many of the best min\ning engineers and copper experts in\nthis part of the country, and past\nachievements have demonstrated that\nthey are in every way fully competent\nto successfully develop this large copper\nproperty.\nCo-operating with Captain Tibby and\nMr. Ely, and acting in an executive\ncapacity, is T. N. McCauley, general\nmanager, who is financing the enter\nprise.\nOn account of having received letters\nof inquiry asking for information re\ngarding these men who have been such\npotent factors in the successful devel\nopment of Mascot to date, we present\nherewith a few extracts from letters of\nendorsement which they have in their\npossession.\nT. N. McCauley, General Manager\nIt has required men formed in a\nheroic mold, and of a type of rugged\nhonesty, to build up the great copper\nindustry of Arizona. Such a man, in\nthe strongest sense of the word, is T.\nN. McCauley. For the past five years\nhe has devoted his time, money and\nenergy in behalf of the Mascot Copper\nCompany, and because of his singleness\nof purpose and the business-like methods\nhe has employed in his work, his efforts\nhave been crowned with superior suc\ncess.\nMr. McCauley has in his possession\nthe largest number of letters of per\nsonal endorsement from bankers, busi\nness, professional and railroad men\ncovering the points referred to in the\nextracts of letters below that it has\never been our pleasure to see, and we\nbelieve the Mascot has got the right\nman in the right place.\nI have known Mr. J. N. McCauley\nfor many years intimately, and have\nhad large business interests with him\n(Concluded on page 4.)\nNO. 46","height":"24657","width":"16455"}}
